<h1>Problem 431 - 2015 Balkan MO, P4 of 4, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Prove that among \(20\) consecutive positive integers there is an integer \(d\) such that for every positive integer \(n\) the following inequality holds
\[n \sqrt{d} \left\{n \sqrt {d} \right \} > \dfrac{5}{2}\]
where by \(\left \{x \right \}\) denotes the fractional part of the real number \(x\). The fractional part of the real number \(x\) is defined as the difference between the largest integer that is less than or equal to \(x\) to the actual number \(x\).</p>
